26 const NONCONFORMING_FUNCTIONS_ERROR_MESSAGE =
27 """
28 Nonconforming functions detected. If a model function `f` is defined
29 as in-place, then all constituant functions like `jac` and `paramjac`
30 must be in-place (and vice versa with out-of-place). Detected that
31 some overloads did not conform to the same convention as `f`.
32 """

34 struct NonconformingFunctionsError <: Exception
35 nonconforming::Vector{String}
36 end

38 function Base.showerror(io::IO, e::NonconformingFunctionsError)

47 abstract type AbstractODEFunction{iip} <: AbstractDiffEqFunction{iip} end
48
49 @doc doc"""
50 ODEFunction{iip,F,TMM,Ta,Tt,TJ,JVP,VJP,JP,SP,TW,TWt,TPJ,S,S2,O,TCV} <: AbstractODEFunction{iip}
51
52 A representation of an ODE function `f`, defined by:
53
54 ```math
55 M \frac{du}{dt} = f(u,p,t)
56 ```
57
58 and all of its related functions, such as the Jacobian of `f`, its gradient
59 with respect to time, and more. For all cases, `u0` is the initial condition,
60 `p` are the parameters, and `t` is the independent variable.
61
62 ## Constructor
63
64 ```julia
65 ODEFunction{iip,recompile}(f;
66 mass_matrix=I,
67 analytic=nothing,
68 tgrad=nothing,
69 jac=nothing,
70 jvp=nothing,
71 vjp=nothing,
72 jac_prototype=nothing,
73 sparsity=jac_prototype,
74 paramjac = nothing,
75 syms = nothing,
76 indepsym = nothing,
77 colorvec = nothing)
78 ```
79
80 Note that only the function `f` itself is required. This function should
81 be given as `f!(du,u,p,t)` or `du = f(u,p,t)`. See the section on `iip`
82 for more details on in-place vs out-of-place handling.
83
84 All of the remaining functions are optional for improving or accelerating
85 the usage of `f`. These include:
86
87 - `mass_matrix`: the mass matrix `M` represented in the ODE function. Can be used
88 to determine that the equation is actually a differential-algebraic equation (DAE)
89 if `M` is singular. Note that in this case special solvers are required, see the
90 DAE solver page for more details: https://diffeq.sciml.ai/stable/solvers/dae_solve/.
91 Must be an AbstractArray or an AbstractSciMLOperator.
92 - `analytic(u0,p,t)`: used to pass an analytical solution function for the analytical
93 solution of the ODE. Generally only used for testing and development of the solvers.
94 - `tgrad(dT,u,p,t)` or dT=tgrad(u,p,t): returns ``\frac{\partial f(u,p,t)}{\partial t}``
95 - `jac(J,u,p,t)` or `J=jac(u,p,t)`: returns ``\frac{df}{du}``
96 - `jvp(Jv,v,u,p,t)` or `Jv=jvp(v,u,p,t)`: returns the directional derivative``\frac{df}{du} v``
97 - `vjp(Jv,v,u,p,t)` or `Jv=vjp(v,u,p,t)`: returns the adjoint derivative``\frac{df}{du}^\ast v``
98 - `jac_prototype`: a prototype matrix matching the type that matches the Jacobian. For example,
99 if the Jacobian is tridiagonal, then an appropriately sized `Tridiagonal` matrix can be used
100 as the prototype and integrators will specialize on this structure where possible. Non-structured
101 sparsity patterns should use a `SparseMatrixCSC` with a correct sparsity pattern for the Jacobian.
102 The default is `nothing`, which means a dense Jacobian.
103 - `paramjac(pJ,u,p,t)`: returns the parameter Jacobian ``\frac{df}{dp}``.
104 - `syms`: the symbol names for the elements of the equation. This should match `u0` in size. For
105 example, if `u0 = [0.0,1.0]` and `syms = [:x, :y]`, this will apply a canonical naming to the
106 values, allowing `sol[:x]` in the solution and automatically naming values in plots.
107 - `indepsym`: the canonical naming for the independent variable. Defaults to nothing, which
108 internally uses `t` as the representation in any plots.
109 - `colorvec`: a color vector according to the SparseDiffTools.jl definition for the sparsity
110 pattern of the `jac_prototype`. This specializes the Jacobian construction when using
111 finite differences and automatic differentiation to be computed in an accelerated manner
112 based on the sparsity pattern. Defaults to `nothing`, which means a color vector will be
113 internally computed on demand when required. The cost of this operation is highly dependent
114 on the sparsity pattern.
115
116 ## iip: In-Place vs Out-Of-Place
117
118 `iip` is the the optional boolean for determining whether a given function is written to
119 be used in-place or out-of-place. In-place functions are `f!(du,u,p,t)` where the return
120 is ignored and the result is expected to be mutated into the value of `du`. Out-of-place
121 functions are `du=f(u,p,t)`.
122
123 Normally this is determined automatically by looking at the method table for `f` and seeing
124 the maximum number of arguments in available dispatches. For this reason, the constructor
125 `ODEFunction(f)` generally works (but is type-unstable). However, for type-stability or
126 to enforce correctness, this option is passed via `ODEFunction{true}(f)`.
127
128 ## recompile: Controlling Compilation and Specialization
129
130 The `recompile` parameter controls whether the ODEFunction will fully specialize on the
131 `typeof(f)`. This causes recompilation of the solver for each new `f` function, but
132 gives the maximum compiler information and runtime speed. By default `recompile = true`.
133 If `recompile = false`, the `ODEFunction` uses `Any` type parameters for each of the
134 functions, allowing for the reuse of compilation caches but adding a dynamic dispatch
135 at the `f` call sites, potentially leading to runtime regressions.
136
137 Overriding the `true` default is done by passing a second type parameter after `iip`,
138 for example `ODEFunction{true,false}(f)` is an in-place function with no recompilation
139 specialization.
140
141 ## Fields
142
143 The fields of the ODEFunction type directly match the names of the inputs.
144
145 ## More Details on Jacobians
146
147 The following example creates an inplace `ODEFunction` whose jacobian is a `Diagonal`:
148
149 ```julia
150 using LinearAlgebra
151 f = (du,u,p,t) -> du .= t .* u
152 jac = (J,u,p,t) -> (J[1,1] = t; J[2,2] = t; J)
153 jp = Diagonal(zeros(2))
154 fun = ODEFunction(f; jac=jac, jac_prototype=jp)
155 ```
156
157 Note that the integrators will always make a deep copy of `fun.jac_prototype`, so
158 there's no worry of aliasing.
159
160 In general the jacobian prototype can be anything that has `mul!` defined, in
161 particular sparse matrices or custom lazy types that support `mul!`. A special case
162 is when the `jac_prototype` is a `AbstractDiffEqLinearOperator`, in which case you
163 do not need to supply `jac` as it is automatically set to `update_coefficients!`.
164 Refer to the AbstractSciMLOperators documentation for more information
165 on setting up time/parameter dependent operators.
166
167 ## Examples
168
169 ### Declaring Explicit Jacobians for ODEs
170
171 The most standard case, declaring a function for a Jacobian is done by overloading
172 the function `f(du,u,p,t)` with an in-place updating function for the Jacobian:
173 `f_jac(J,u,p,t)` where the value type is used for dispatch. For example,
174 take the LotkaVolterra model:
175
176 ```julia
177 function f(du,u,p,t)
178 du[1] = 2.0 * u[1] - 1.2 * u[1]*u[2]
179 du[2] = -3 * u[2] + u[1]*u[2]
180 end
181 ```
182
183 To declare the Jacobian we simply add the dispatch:
184
185 ```julia
186 function f_jac(J,u,p,t)
187 J[1,1] = 2.0 - 1.2 * u[2]
188 J[1,2] = -1.2 * u[1]
189 J[2,1] = 1 * u[2]
190 J[2,2] = -3 + u[1]
191 nothing
192 end
193 ```
194
195 Then we can supply the Jacobian with our ODE as:
196
197 ```julia
198 ff = ODEFunction(f;jac=f_jac)
199 ```
200
201 and use this in an `ODEProblem`:
202
203 ```julia
204 prob = ODEProblem(ff,ones(2),(0.0,10.0))
205 ```
206
207 ## Symbolically Generating the Functions
208
209 See the `modelingtoolkitize` function from
210 [ModelingToolkit.jl](https://github.com/JuliaDiffEq/ModelingToolkit.jl) for
211 automatically symbolically generating the Jacobian and more from the
212 numerically-defined functions.
213 """

216 mass_matrix::TMM
217 analytic::Ta
218 tgrad::Tt
219 jac::TJ
220 jvp::JVP
221 vjp::VJP
222 jac_prototype::JP
223 sparsity::SP
224 Wfact::TW
225 Wfact_t::TWt
226 paramjac::TPJ
227 syms::S
228 indepsym::S2
229 observed::O
230 colorvec::TCV
231 end

233 @doc doc"""
234 SplitFunction{iip,F1,F2,TMM,C,Ta,Tt,TJ,JVP,VJP,JP,SP,TW,TWt,TPJ,S,O,TCV} <: AbstractODEFunction{iip}
235
236 A representation of a split ODE function `f`, defined by:
237
238 ```math
239 M \frac{du}{dt} = f_1(u,p,t) + f_2(u,p,t)
240 ```
241
242 and all of its related functions, such as the Jacobian of `f`, its gradient
243 with respect to time, and more. For all cases, `u0` is the initial condition,
244 `p` are the parameters, and `t` is the independent variable.
245
246 Generally, for ODE integrators the `f_1` portion should be considered the
247 "stiff portion of the model" with larger time scale separation, while the
248 `f_2` portion should be considered the "non-stiff portion". This interpretation
249 is directly used in integrators like IMEX (implicit-explicit integrators)
250 and exponential integrators.
251
252 ## Constructor
253
254 ```julia
255 SplitFunction{iip,recompile}(f1,f2;
256 mass_matrix=I,
257 analytic=nothing,
258 tgrad=nothing,
259 jac=nothing,
260 jvp=nothing,
261 vjp=nothing,
262 jac_prototype=nothing,
263 sparsity=jac_prototype,
264 paramjac = nothing,
265 syms = nothing,
266 indepsym = nothing,
267 colorvec = nothing)
268 ```
269
270 Note that only the functions `f_i` themselves are required. These functions should
271 be given as `f_i!(du,u,p,t)` or `du = f_i(u,p,t)`. See the section on `iip`
272 for more details on in-place vs out-of-place handling.
273
274 All of the remaining functions are optional for improving or accelerating
275 the usage of `f`. These include:
276
277 - `mass_matrix`: the mass matrix `M` represented in the ODE function. Can be used
278 to determine that the equation is actually a differential-algebraic equation (DAE)
279 if `M` is singular. Note that in this case special solvers are required, see the
280 DAE solver page for more details: https://diffeq.sciml.ai/stable/solvers/dae_solve/.
281 Must be an AbstractArray or an AbstractSciMLOperator.
282 - `analytic(u0,p,t)`: used to pass an analytical solution function for the analytical
283 solution of the ODE. Generally only used for testing and development of the solvers.
284 - `tgrad(dT,u,p,t)` or dT=tgrad(u,p,t): returns ``\frac{\partial f_1(u,p,t)}{\partial t}``
285 - `jac(J,u,p,t)` or `J=jac(u,p,t)`: returns ``\frac{df_1}{du}``
286 - `jvp(Jv,v,u,p,t)` or `Jv=jvp(v,u,p,t)`: returns the directional derivative``\frac{df_1}{du} v``
287 - `vjp(Jv,v,u,p,t)` or `Jv=vjp(v,u,p,t)`: returns the adjoint derivative``\frac{df_1}{du}^\ast v``
288 - `jac_prototype`: a prototype matrix matching the type that matches the Jacobian. For example,
289 if the Jacobian is tridiagonal, then an appropriately sized `Tridiagonal` matrix can be used
290 as the prototype and integrators will specialize on this structure where possible. Non-structured
291 sparsity patterns should use a `SparseMatrixCSC` with a correct sparsity pattern for the Jacobian.
292 The default is `nothing`, which means a dense Jacobian.
293 - `paramjac(pJ,u,p,t)`: returns the parameter Jacobian ``\frac{df_1}{dp}``.
294 - `syms`: the symbol names for the elements of the equation. This should match `u0` in size. For
295 example, if `u0 = [0.0,1.0]` and `syms = [:x, :y]`, this will apply a canonical naming to the
296 values, allowing `sol[:x]` in the solution and automatically naming values in plots.
297 - `indepsym`: the canonical naming for the independent variable. Defaults to nothing, which
298 internally uses `t` as the representation in any plots.
299 - `colorvec`: a color vector according to the SparseDiffTools.jl definition for the sparsity
300 pattern of the `jac_prototype`. This specializes the Jacobian construction when using
301 finite differences and automatic differentiation to be computed in an accelerated manner
302 based on the sparsity pattern. Defaults to `nothing`, which means a color vector will be
303 internally computed on demand when required. The cost of this operation is highly dependent
304 on the sparsity pattern.
305
306 ## Note on the Derivative Definition
307
308 The derivatives, such as the Jacobian, are only defined on the `f1` portion of the split ODE.
309 This is used to treat the `f1` implicit while keeping the `f2` portion explicit.
310
311 ## iip: In-Place vs Out-Of-Place
312
313 For more details on this argument, see the ODEFunction documentation.
314
315 ## recompile: Controlling Compilation and Specialization
316
317 For more details on this argument, see the ODEFunction documentation.

320
321 The fields of the SplitFunction type directly match the names of the inputs.

323 ## Symbolically Generating the Functions
324
325 See the `modelingtoolkitize` function from
326 [ModelingToolkit.jl](https://github.com/JuliaDiffEq/ModelingToolkit.jl) for
327 automatically symbolically generating the Jacobian and more from the
328 numerically-defined functions. See `ModelingToolkit.SplitODEProblem` for
329 information on generating the SplitFunction from this symbolic engine.

562 @doc doc"""
563 DynamicalDDEFunction{iip,F1,F2,TMM,Ta,Tt,TJ,JVP,VJP,JP,SP,TW,TWt,TPJ,S,O,TCV} <: AbstractDDEFunction{iip}
564
565 A representation of a DDE function `f`, defined by:
566
567 ```math
568 M \frac{du}{dt} = f(u,h,p,t)
569 ```
570
571 as a partitioned ODE:
572
573 ```math
574 M_1 \frac{du}{dt} = f_1(u,h,p,t)
575 M_2 \frac{du}{dt} = f_2(u,h,p,t)
576 ```
577
578 and all of its related functions, such as the Jacobian of `f`, its gradient
579 with respect to time, and more. For all cases, `u0` is the initial condition,
580 `p` are the parameters, and `t` is the independent variable.
581
582 ## Constructor
583
584 ```julia
585 DynamicalDDEFunction{iip,recompile}(f1,f2;
586 mass_matrix=I,
587 analytic=nothing,
588 tgrad=nothing,
589 jac=nothing,
590 jvp=nothing,
591 vjp=nothing,
592 jac_prototype=nothing,
593 sparsity=jac_prototype,
594 paramjac = nothing,
595 syms = nothing,
596 indepsym = nothing,
597 colorvec = nothing)
598 ```
599
600 Note that only the functions `f_i` themselves are required. These functions should
601 be given as `f_i!(du,u,h,p,t)` or `du = f_i(u,h,p,t)`. See the section on `iip`
602 for more details on in-place vs out-of-place handling. The histroy function
603 `h` acts as an interpolator over time, i.e. `h(t)` with options matching
604 the solution interface, i.e. `h(t; save_idxs = 2)`.
605
606 All of the remaining functions are optional for improving or accelerating
607 the usage of `f`. These include:
608
609 - `mass_matrix`: the mass matrix `M_i` represented in the ODE function. Can be used
610 to determine that the equation is actually a differential-algebraic equation (DAE)
611 if `M` is singular. Note that in this case special solvers are required, see the
612 DAE solver page for more details: https://diffeq.sciml.ai/stable/solvers/dae_solve/.
613 Must be an AbstractArray or an AbstractSciMLOperator. Should be given as a tuple
614 of mass matrices, i.e. `(M_1, M_2)` for the mass matrices of equations 1 and 2
615 respectively.
616 - `analytic(u0,h,p,t)`: used to pass an analytical solution function for the analytical
617 solution of the ODE. Generally only used for testing and development of the solvers.
618 - `tgrad(dT,u,h,p,t)` or dT=tgrad(u,h,p,t): returns ``\frac{\partial f(u,p,t)}{\partial t}``
619 - `jac(J,u,h,p,t)` or `J=jac(u,h,p,t)`: returns ``\frac{df}{du}``
620 - `jvp(Jv,v,u,h,p,t)` or `Jv=jvp(v,u,h,p,t)`: returns the directional derivative``\frac{df}{du} v``
621 - `vjp(Jv,v,u,h,p,t)` or `Jv=vjp(v,u,h,p,t)`: returns the adjoint derivative``\frac{df}{du}^\ast v``
622 - `jac_prototype`: a prototype matrix matching the type that matches the Jacobian. For example,
623 if the Jacobian is tridiagonal, then an appropriately sized `Tridiagonal` matrix can be used
624 as the prototype and integrators will specialize on this structure where possible. Non-structured
625 sparsity patterns should use a `SparseMatrixCSC` with a correct sparsity pattern for the Jacobian.
626 The default is `nothing`, which means a dense Jacobian.
627 - `paramjac(pJ,u,h,p,t)`: returns the parameter Jacobian ``\frac{df}{dp}``.
628 - `syms`: the symbol names for the elements of the equation. This should match `u0` in size. For
629 example, if `u0 = [0.0,1.0]` and `syms = [:x, :y]`, this will apply a canonical naming to the
630 values, allowing `sol[:x]` in the solution and automatically naming values in plots.
631 - `indepsym`: the canonical naming for the independent variable. Defaults to nothing, which
632 internally uses `t` as the representation in any plots.
633 - `colorvec`: a color vector according to the SparseDiffTools.jl definition for the sparsity
634 pattern of the `jac_prototype`. This specializes the Jacobian construction when using
635 finite differences and automatic differentiation to be computed in an accelerated manner
636 based on the sparsity pattern. Defaults to `nothing`, which means a color vector will be
637 internally computed on demand when required. The cost of this operation is highly dependent
638 on the sparsity pattern.
639
640 ## iip: In-Place vs Out-Of-Place
641
642 For more details on this argument, see the ODEFunction documentation.
643
644 ## recompile: Controlling Compilation and Specialization
645
646 For more details on this argument, see the ODEFunction documentation.
647
648 ## Fields
649
650 The fields of the DynamicalDDEFunction type directly match the names of the inputs.
651 """
652 struct DynamicalDDEFunction{iip,F1,F2,TMM,Ta,Tt,TJ,JVP,VJP,JP,SP,TW,TWt,TPJ,S,O,TCV} <: AbstractDDEFunction{iip}
653 f1::F1
654 f2::F2
655 mass_matrix::TMM
656 analytic::Ta
657 tgrad::Tt
658 jac::TJ
659 jvp::JVP
660 vjp::VJP
661 jac_prototype::JP
662 sparsity::SP
663 Wfact::TW
664 Wfact_t::TWt
665 paramjac::TPJ
666 syms::S
667 observed::O
668 colorvec::TCV
669 end

836 @doc doc"""
837 SplitSDEFunction{iip,F1,F2,G,TMM,C,Ta,Tt,TJ,JVP,VJP,JP,SP,TW,TWt,TPJ,S,O,TCV} <: AbstractSDEFunction{iip}
838
839 A representation of a split SDE function `f`, defined by:
840
841 ```math
842 M \frac{du}{dt} = f_1(u,p,t) + f_2(u,p,t) + g(u,p,t) dW
843 ```
844
845 and all of its related functions, such as the Jacobian of `f`, its gradient
846 with respect to time, and more. For all cases, `u0` is the initial condition,
847 `p` are the parameters, and `t` is the independent variable.
848
849 Generally, for SDE integrators the `f_1` portion should be considered the
850 "stiff portion of the model" with larger time scale separation, while the
851 `f_2` portion should be considered the "non-stiff portion". This interpretation
852 is directly used in integrators like IMEX (implicit-explicit integrators)
853 and exponential integrators.
854
855 ## Constructor
856
857 ```julia
858 SplitSDEFunction{iip,recompile}(f1,f2,g;
859 mass_matrix=I,
860 analytic=nothing,
861 tgrad=nothing,
862 jac=nothing,
863 jvp=nothing,
864 vjp=nothing,
865 ggprime = nothing,
866 jac_prototype=nothing,
867 sparsity=jac_prototype,
868 paramjac = nothing,
869 syms = nothing,
870 indepsym = nothing,
871 colorvec = nothing)
872 ```
873
874 Note that only the function `f` itself is required. All of the remaining functions
875 are optional for improving or accelerating the usage of `f`. These include:
876
877 - `mass_matrix`: the mass matrix `M` represented in the SDE function. Can be used
878 to determine that the equation is actually a stochastic differential-algebraic equation (SDAE)
879 if `M` is singular. Note that in this case special solvers are required, see the
880 DAE solver page for more details: https://diffeq.sciml.ai/stable/solvers/sdae_solve/.
881 Must be an AbstractArray or an AbstractSciMLOperator.
882 - `analytic(u0,p,t)`: used to pass an analytical solution function for the analytical
883 solution of the ODE. Generally only used for testing and development of the solvers.
884 - `tgrad(dT,u,p,t)` or dT=tgrad(u,p,t): returns ``\frac{\partial f_1(u,p,t)}{\partial t}``
885 - `jac(J,u,p,t)` or `J=jac(u,p,t)`: returns ``\frac{df_1}{du}``
886 - `jvp(Jv,v,u,p,t)` or `Jv=jvp(v,u,p,t)`: returns the directional derivative``\frac{df_1}{du} v``
887 - `vjp(Jv,v,u,p,t)` or `Jv=vjp(v,u,p,t)`: returns the adjoint derivative``\frac{df_1}{du}^\ast v``
888 - `ggprime(J,u,p,t)` or `J = ggprime(u,p,t)`: returns the Milstein derivative
889 ``\frac{dg(u,p,t)}{du} g(u,p,t)``
890 - `jac_prototype`: a prototype matrix matching the type that matches the Jacobian. For example,
891 if the Jacobian is tridiagonal, then an appropriately sized `Tridiagonal` matrix can be used
892 as the prototype and integrators will specialize on this structure where possible. Non-structured
893 sparsity patterns should use a `SparseMatrixCSC` with a correct sparsity pattern for the Jacobian.
894 The default is `nothing`, which means a dense Jacobian.
895 - `paramjac(pJ,u,p,t)`: returns the parameter Jacobian ``\frac{df_1}{dp}``.
896 - `syms`: the symbol names for the elements of the equation. This should match `u0` in size. For
897 example, if `u0 = [0.0,1.0]` and `syms = [:x, :y]`, this will apply a canonical naming to the
898 values, allowing `sol[:x]` in the solution and automatically naming values in plots.
899 - `indepsym`: the canonical naming for the independent variable. Defaults to nothing, which
900 internally uses `t` as the representation in any plots.
901 - `colorvec`: a color vector according to the SparseDiffTools.jl definition for the sparsity
902 pattern of the `jac_prototype`. This specializes the Jacobian construction when using
903 finite differences and automatic differentiation to be computed in an accelerated manner
904 based on the sparsity pattern. Defaults to `nothing`, which means a color vector will be
905 internally computed on demand when required. The cost of this operation is highly dependent
906 on the sparsity pattern.
907
908 ## Note on the Derivative Definition
909
910 The derivatives, such as the Jacobian, are only defined on the `f1` portion of the split ODE.
911 This is used to treat the `f1` implicit while keeping the `f2` portion explicit.
912
913 ## iip: In-Place vs Out-Of-Place
914
915 For more details on this argument, see the ODEFunction documentation.
916
917 ## recompile: Controlling Compilation and Specialization
918
919 For more details on this argument, see the ODEFunction documentation.

921 ## Fields

923 The fields of the SplitSDEFunction type directly match the names of the inputs.

1096 be given as `f!(du,u,p,t)` or `du = f(u,p,t)`. See the section on `iip`
1097 for more details on in-place vs out-of-place handling.
1098
1099 All of the remaining functions are optional for improving or accelerating
1100 the usage of `f`. These include:
1101
1102 - `mass_matrix`: the mass matrix `M` represented in the ODE function. Can be used
1103 to determine that the equation is actually a differential-algebraic equation (DAE)
1104 if `M` is singular. Note that in this case special solvers are required, see the
1105 DAE solver page for more details: https://diffeq.sciml.ai/stable/solvers/dae_solve/.
1106 Must be an AbstractArray or an AbstractSciMLOperator.
1107 - `analytic(u0,p,t)`: used to pass an analytical solution function for the analytical
1108 solution of the ODE. Generally only used for testing and development of the solvers.
1109 - `tgrad(dT,u,p,t)` or dT=tgrad(u,p,t): returns ``\frac{\partial f(u,p,t)}{\partial t}``
1110 - `jac(J,u,p,t)` or `J=jac(u,p,t)`: returns ``\frac{df}{du}``
1111 - `jvp(Jv,v,u,p,t)` or `Jv=jvp(v,u,p,t)`: returns the directional derivative``\frac{df}{du} v``
1112 - `vjp(Jv,v,u,p,t)` or `Jv=vjp(v,u,p,t)`: returns the adjoint derivative``\frac{df}{du}^\ast v``
1113 - `jac_prototype`: a prototype matrix matching the type that matches the Jacobian. For example,
1114 if the Jacobian is tridiagonal, then an appropriately sized `Tridiagonal` matrix can be used
1115 as the prototype and integrators will specialize on this structure where possible. Non-structured
1116 sparsity patterns should use a `SparseMatrixCSC` with a correct sparsity pattern for the Jacobian.
1117 The default is `nothing`, which means a dense Jacobian.
1118 - `paramjac(pJ,u,p,t)`: returns the parameter Jacobian ``\frac{df}{dp}``.
1119 - `syms`: the symbol names for the elements of the equation. This should match `u0` in size. For
1120 example, if `u0 = [0.0,1.0]` and `syms = [:x, :y]`, this will apply a canonical naming to the
1121 values, allowing `sol[:x]` in the solution and automatically naming values in plots.
1122 - `indepsym`: the canonical naming for the independent variable. Defaults to nothing, which
1123 internally uses `t` as the representation in any plots.
1124 - `colorvec`: a color vector according to the SparseDiffTools.jl definition for the sparsity
1125 pattern of the `jac_prototype`. This specializes the Jacobian construction when using
1126 finite differences and automatic differentiation to be computed in an accelerated manner
1127 based on the sparsity pattern. Defaults to `nothing`, which means a color vector will be
1128 internally computed on demand when required. The cost of this operation is highly dependent
1129 on the sparsity pattern.
1130
1131 ## iip: In-Place vs Out-Of-Place
1132
1133 For more details on this argument, see the ODEFunction documentation.
1134
1135 ## recompile: Controlling Compilation and Specialization

1137 For more details on this argument, see the ODEFunction documentation.

1169 A representation of an implicit DAE function `f`, defined by:

1203 - `jac(J,du,u,p,gamma,t)` or `J=jac(du,u,p,gamma,t)`: returns the implicit DAE Jacobian
1204 defined as ``gamma \frac{dG}{d(du)} + \frac{dG}{du}``
1205 - `jvp(Jv,v,du,u,p,gamma,t)` or `Jv=jvp(v,du,u,p,gamma,t)`: returns the directional
1206 derivative``\frac{df}{du} v``
1207 - `vjp(Jv,v,du,u,p,gamma,t)` or `Jv=vjp(v,du,u,p,gamma,t)`: returns the adjoint

1212 sparsity patterns should use a `SparseMatrixCSC` with a correct sparsity pattern for the Jacobian.

1234 ## Fields

1237
1238 ## Examples
1239
1240
1241 ### Declaring Explicit Jacobians for DAEs
1242
1243 For fully implicit ODEs (`DAEProblem`s), a slightly different Jacobian function
1244 is necessary. For the DAE
1245
1246 ```math
1247 G(du,u,p,t) = res
1248 ```
1249
1250 The Jacobian should be given in the form `gamma*dG/d(du) + dG/du ` where `gamma`
1251 is given by the solver. This means that the signature is:
1252
1253 ```julia
1254 f(J,du,u,p,gamma,t)
1255 ```
1256
1257 For example, for the equation
1258
1259 ```julia
1260 function testjac(res,du,u,p,t)
1261 res[1] = du[1] - 2.0 * u[1] + 1.2 * u[1]*u[2]
1262 res[2] = du[2] -3 * u[2] - u[1]*u[2]
1263 end
1264 ```
1265
1266 we would define the Jacobian as:
1267
1268 ```julia
1269 function testjac(J,du,u,p,gamma,t)
1270 J[1,1] = gamma - 2.0 + 1.2 * u[2]
1271 J[1,2] = 1.2 * u[1]
1272 J[2,1] = - 1 * u[2]
1273 J[2,2] = gamma - 3 - u[1]
1274 nothing
1275 end
1276 ```
1277
1278 ## Symbolically Generating the Functions
1279
1280 See the `modelingtoolkitize` function from
1281 [ModelingToolkit.jl](https://github.com/JuliaDiffEq/ModelingToolkit.jl) for
1282 automatically symbolically generating the Jacobian and more from the
1283 numerically-defined functions.
1284 """
1285 struct DAEFunction{iip,F,Ta,Tt,TJ,JVP,VJP,JP,SP,TW,TWt,TPJ,S,O,TCV} <: AbstractDAEFunction{iip}
1286 f::F
1287 analytic::Ta
1288 tgrad::Tt
1289 jac::TJ
1290 jvp::JVP
1291 vjp::VJP
1292 jac_prototype::JP
1293 sparsity::SP
1294 Wfact::TW
1295 Wfact_t::TWt
1296 paramjac::TPJ
1297 syms::S
1298 observed::O
1299 colorvec::TCV
1300 end

1503 """
1504 OptimizationFunction{iip,AD,F,G,H,HV,C,CJ,CH,HP,CJP,CHP,S,HCV,CJCV,CHCV} <: AbstractOptimizationFunction{iip}
1505
1506 A representation of an optimization of an objective function `f`, defined by:
1507
1508 ```math
1509 min_{u} f(u,p)
1510 ```
1511
1512 and all of its related functions, such as the gradient of `f`, its Hessian,
1513 and more. For all cases, `u` is the state and `p` are the parameters.
1514
1515 ## Constructor
1516
1517 OptimizationFunction{iip}(f,adtype::AbstractADType=NoAD();
1518 grad=nothing,hess=nothing,hv=nothing,
1519 cons=nothing, cons_j=nothing,cons_h=nothing,
1520 hess_prototype=nothing,cons_jac_prototype=nothing,
1521 cons_hess_prototype = nothing,
1522 syms = nothing, hess_colorvec = nothing,
1523 cons_jac_colorvec = nothing,
1524 cons_hess_colorvec = nothing)
1525
1526 - `adtype`: see the section "Defining Optimization Functions via AD"
1527 - `grad(G,u,p)` or `G=grad(u,p)`: the gradient of `f` with respect to `u`
1528 - `hess(H,u,p)` or `H=hess(u,p)`: the Hessian of `f` with respect to `u`
1529 - `hv(Hv,u,v,p)` or `Hv=hv(u,v,p)`: the Hessian-vector product ``\frac{d^2 f}{du^2} v``.
1530 - `cons(res,x,p)` or `res=cons(x,p)`: the equality constraints vector, where the constraints
1531 are satisfied when `res = 0`.
1532 - `cons_j(res,x,p)` or `res=cons_j(x,p)`: the Jacobian of the equality constraints.
1533 - `cons_h(res,x,p)` or `res=cons_h(x,p)`: the Hessian of the equality constratins, provided as
1534 and array of Hessians with `res[i]` being the Hessian with respect to the `i`th output on `cons`.
1535 - `paramjac(pJ,u,p)`: returns the parameter Jacobian ``\frac{df}{dp}``.
1536 - `hess_prototype`: a prototype matrix matching the type that matches the Hessian. For example,
1537 if the Hessian is tridiagonal, then an appropriately sized `Hessian` matrix can be used
1538 as the prototype and integrators will specialize on this structure where possible. Non-structured
1539 sparsity patterns should use a `SparseMatrixCSC` with a correct sparsity pattern for the Hessian.
1540 The default is `nothing`, which means a dense Hessian.
1541 - `cons_jac_prototype`: a prototype matrix matching the type that matches the constraint Jacobian.
1542 The default is `nothing`, which means a dense constraint Jacobian.
1543 - `cons_hess_prototype`: a prototype matrix matching the type that matches the constraint Hessian.
1544 This is defined as an array of matrices, where `hess[i]` is the Hessian w.r.t. the `i`th output.
1545 For example, if the Hessian is sparse, then `hess` is a `Vector{SparseMatrixCSC}`.
1546 The default is `nothing`, which means a dense constraint Hessian.
1547 - `syms`: the symbol names for the elements of the equation. This should match `u0` in size. For
1548 example, if `u = [0.0,1.0]` and `syms = [:x, :y]`, this will apply a canonical naming to the
1549 values, allowing `sol[:x]` in the solution and automatically naming values in plots.
1550 - `hess_colorvec`: a color vector according to the SparseDiffTools.jl definition for the sparsity
1551 pattern of the `hess_prototype`. This specializes the Hessian construction when using
1552 finite differences and automatic differentiation to be computed in an accelerated manner
1553 based on the sparsity pattern. Defaults to `nothing`, which means a color vector will be
1554 internally computed on demand when required. The cost of this operation is highly dependent
1555 on the sparsity pattern.
1556 - `cons_jac_colorvec`: a color vector according to the SparseDiffTools.jl definition for the sparsity
1557 pattern of the `cons_jac_prototype`.
1558 - `cons_hess_colorvec`: an array of color vector according to the SparseDiffTools.jl definition for
1559 the sparsity pattern of the `cons_hess_prototype`.
1560
1561 ## Defining Optimization Functions Via AD
1562
1563 While using the keyword arguments gives the user control over defining
1564 all of the possible functions, the simplest way to handle the generation
1565 of an `OptimizationFunction` is by specifying an AD type. By doing so,
1566 this will automatically fill in all of the extra functions. For example,
1567
1568 ```julia
1569 OptimizationFunction(f,AutoZygote())
1570 ```
1571
1572 will use [Zygote.jl](https://github.com/FluxML/Zygote.jl) to define
1573 all of the necessary functions. Note that if any functions are defined
1574 directly, the auto-AD definition does not overwrite the user's choice.
1575
1576 Each of the AD-based constructors are documented separately via their
1577 own dispatches.
1578
1579 ## iip: In-Place vs Out-Of-Place
1580
1581 For more details on this argument, see the ODEFunction documentation.
1582
1583 ## recompile: Controlling Compilation and Specialization
1584
1585 For more details on this argument, see the ODEFunction documentation.
1586
1587 ## Fields
1588
1589 The fields of the OptimizationFunction type directly match the names of the inputs.
1590 """
1591 struct OptimizationFunction{iip,AD,F,G,H,HV,C,CJ,CH,HP,CJP,CHP,S,HCV,CJCV,CHCV,EX,CEX} <: AbstractOptimizationFunction{iip}
1592 f::F
1593 adtype::AD
1594 grad::G
1595 hess::H
1596 hv::HV
1597 cons::C
1598 cons_j::CJ
1599 cons_h::CH
1600 hess_prototype::HP
1601 cons_jac_prototype::CJP
1602 cons_hess_prototype::CHP
1603 syms::S
1604 hess_colorvec::HCV
1605 cons_jac_colorvec::CJCV
1606 cons_hess_colorvec::CHCV
1607 expr::EX
1608 cons_expr::CEX
1609 end

2634 vjpiip = vjp !== nothing ? isinplace(vjp,4,"vjp") : iip

2636 nonconforming = (jaciip,jvpiip,vjpiip) .!= iip
2637 if any(nonconforming)
2638 nonconforming = findall(nonconforming)
2639 functions = ["jac","jvp","vjp"][nonconforming]
2640 throw(NonconformingFunctionsError(functions))
2641 end

2644 typeof(f), typeof(mass_matrix), typeof(analytic), typeof(tgrad), typeof(jac),
2645 typeof(jvp), typeof(vjp), typeof(jac_prototype), typeof(sparsity), typeof(Wfact),
2646 typeof(Wfact_t), typeof(paramjac), typeof(syms), typeof(observed), typeof(_colorvec)}(
2647 f, mass_matrix, analytic, tgrad, jac,
2648 jvp, vjp, jac_prototype, sparsity, Wfact,
2649 Wfact_t, paramjac, syms, observed, _colorvec)
2650 end

2652 function NonlinearFunction{iip,false}(f;
2653 mass_matrix=I,
2654 analytic=nothing,
2655 tgrad=nothing,
2656 jac=nothing,
2657 jvp=nothing,
2658 vjp=nothing,
2659 jac_prototype=nothing,
2660 sparsity=jac_prototype,
2661 Wfact=nothing,
2662 Wfact_t=nothing,
2663 paramjac = nothing,
2664 syms = nothing,
2665 observed = DEFAULT_OBSERVED_NO_TIME,
2666 colorvec = nothing) where iip
2667
2668 if jac === nothing && isa(jac_prototype, AbstractDiffEqLinearOperator)
2669 if iip
2670 jac = update_coefficients! #(J,u,p,t)
2671 else
2672 jac = (u,p,t) -> update_coefficients!(deepcopy(jac_prototype),u,p,t)
2673 end
2674 end
2675
2676 if jac_prototype !== nothing && colorvec === nothing && ArrayInterfaceCore.fast_matrix_colors(jac_prototype)
2677 _colorvec = ArrayInterfaceCore.matrix_colors(jac_prototype)
2678 else
2679 _colorvec = colorvec
2680 end

2688 Wfact_t, paramjac, syms, observed, _colorvec)
2689 end
